Dogs are not safe because of lions in cages.

Because the original type (`List`) is used, the generic feature is lost, and it cannot be checked at compile time. The error will be left in the code and leaked at runtime (that is, the dog was eaten by a lion)

When you can ensure that the data in your collection is safe, then you can use `@SupressWarnings` to ignore compile-time checks.

For example, if your `getCage` method is written like this, you can guarantee type safety

    public Cage getCage() {
        List cage = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
        cage.add(new Dog()); // Here, instead of putting a lion in a cage, a dog is put in a cage
        cage.add(new Dog());
        return new Cage(cage);
    }


For your code, I think it is safe. just use `@SupressWarnings` to ignore compile-time checks.

